"Jónsson T., Hanna E.","A new day-to-day pressure variability index as a proxy of Icelandic storminess and complement to the North Atlantic Oscillation index 1823-2005",2007,"Meteorologische Zeitschrift","16","1",,"25","36",,,10.1127/0941-2948/2007/0177,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33947430977&partnerID=40&md5=6db0976e1b20a44fe377e487c31a1fc7","Icelandic Meteorological Office, Bustadavegur 9, Reykjavík 150, Iceland; Department of Geography, University of Sheffield, Sheffield, United Kingdom","Jónsson, T., Icelandic Meteorological Office, Bustadavegur 9, Reykjavík 150, Iceland; Hanna, E., Department of Geography, University of Sheffield, Sheffield, United Kingdom","As unknown instrument index errors might affect the accuracy of the early parts of the long-term baseline North Atlantic Oscillation (NAO) indices, it is of interest to find alternative means for an assessment of the behavior of the NAO. Our novel day-to-day pressure variability index (dp) introduced in this paper shows interesting secular variability that is in some sense a 'measure' of the proximity of the Atlantic storm track to Iceland and thus also an independent measure of the activity of the NAO. Like the NAO indices, dp is significantly negatively (positively) correlated with temperature in western Greenland (north-west Europe). There is a significant correlation between the dp index and average wind speed at the Icelandic stations (for the time of available wind records). This correlation becomes especially prominent at multi-year time scales, but is also evident at the scale of individual months. There is no evidence of a global warming signal in this storminess proxy. © by Gebrüder Borntraeger 2007.",,"Atmospheric pressure; Correlation methods; Meteorology; Storms; Wind; air temperature; atmospheric pressure; global warming; North Atlantic Oscillation; secular variation; storm; wind velocity; Arctic; Greenland; Iceland",,,,,,"Alexander, L.V., Tett, S.F.B., Jónsson, T., Recent observed changes in severe storms over the United Kingdom and Iceland (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett., 32. , L13704, Doi: 10.1029/2005GL022371; Ansell, T.J., Jones, P.D., Allan, R.J., Lister, D., Parker, D.E., Brunet, M., Moberg, A., Xoplaki, E., Daily mean sea level pressure reconstructions for the European - North Atlantic region for the period 1850-2003 (2006) J. Climate, 19, pp. 2717-2742; Ayrault, F., Lalaurette, F., Joly, A., Loo, C., North-Atlantic ultra-high frequency variability - An introductory survey (1995) Tellus A, 47, pp. 671-696; Bärring, L., von Storch, H., Scandinavian storminess since about 1800 (2004) Geophys. Res. Lett., 31. , L20202, Doi: 10.1029/2004GL020441; Benedict, J.J., Lee, S., Fieldstein, S.B., Synoptic view of the North Atlantic Oscillation (2004) J. Atmos. Sci., 61, pp. 121-144; Bergström, H., Moberg, A., Daily air temperature and pressure series for Uppsala (1722-1998) (2002) Climate Change, 53, pp. 213-252; Blackmon, M.L., Climatological spectral study of 500 mb geopotential height of Northern Hemisphere (1976) J. Atmos. Sci., 33 (8), pp. 1607-1623; Cappelen, J., DMI Annual Climate Collection 1873-2005, Denmark, the Faroe Islands and Greenland (2006) DMI Technical Report 06-08, , Danish Meteorological Institute, Copenhagen; Cappelen, J., Laursen, E.V., Jorgensen, P.V., Kern-Hansen, C., DMI Monthly Climate Collection 1768-2004, Denmark, the Faroe Islands and Greenland (2005) DMI Technical Report 05-05, , Danish Meteorological Institute, Copenhagen; Carretero, J.C., Changing waves and storms in the northeast Atlantic? (1998) Bull. Amer. Met. Soc., 79, pp. 741-760. , The WASA Group; Chang, E.K.M., Fu, Y.F., Interdecadal variations in Northern Hemisphere winter storm track intensity (2002) J. Climate, 15, pp. 642-658; Chang, E.K.M., Lee, S.Y., Swanson, K.L., Storm track dynamics (2002) J. Climate, 15, pp. 2163-2183; Cullather, R., Lynch, A.H., The annual cycle and interannual variability of atmospheric pressure in the vicinity of the Nor